## Project Overview
Wallet Share Protection is designed to identify high-value UAE customers who are quietly reducing the variety of categories they buy from before they fully disengage. In retail loyalty programs, a shrinking category footprint is often an earlier and more actionable signal than a complete drop in spend. A customer who once bought across grocery, fresh food, electronics, and fashion but now shops in only one or two areas is showing early wallet-share erosion.

This notebook builds an end-to-end machine learning pipeline to detect that pattern in a business-ready way. It starts by assembling nine months of customer, transaction, and product hierarchy data, then converts raw transaction lines into a monthly view of category breadth, spend, and visits at the `customer_id` level. From there, it labels sustained three-month decline events, engineers trajectory features that capture both the level and direction of change, and trains a Cox Proportional Hazards model to estimate the likelihood that a customer will soon consolidate their purchases further.

The output is designed for commercial action rather than academic analysis. Each active customer receives a normalized hazard score, a clear risk tier, and a trajectory segment such as Gradual Consolidator or Sudden Dropper. That combination helps CRM teams decide not only who to target first, but also what kind of intervention is most appropriate, such as cross-sell offers, win-back campaigns, or positive reinforcement for recovering customers.

The final result is persisted to a Delta table so that downstream reporting, Genie Spaces, and CRM audience extraction can operate from one governed source of truth. The recommended operating model is a weekly scoring cycle, allowing LuLu Group International to refresh early-warning signals regularly and protect wallet share before high-value customers become materially harder to win back.

