### What Step 5 Did

**What Is a Cox Proportional Hazards Model?**

The Cox PH model estimates the **instantaneous risk (hazard)** that a customer will experience the consolidation event at any given point in time, based on their characteristics. Unlike classification which predicts yes/no, Cox models the **timing** of events and properly handles customers who haven't had the event yet (censored).

**Reading the Model Output:**

| Metric | What It Means |
|--------|---------------|
| **Coefficient (coef)** | Log of the hazard ratio. Positive = increases risk, Negative = decreases risk |
| **Hazard Ratio (exp(coef))** | Multiplicative effect on risk. HR=2.0 means 2x higher risk per unit increase |
| **p-value** | Statistical significance. p < 0.05 means the effect is unlikely due to chance |
| **Concordance Index** | How well the model ranks customers by risk. 0.5 = random, 1.0 = perfect |

**Example Interpretation:**

If `breadth_slope` has coefficient = -1.5 and HR = 0.22:
- A **negative slope** (category breadth declining over time) **increases** risk
- Each unit decrease in slope multiplies the baseline hazard by ~4.5x (1/0.22)
- Customers with declining breadth trajectories are much more likely to consolidate soon

**What Does Concordance Index Mean in Plain English?**

If we randomly pick two customers — one who experienced the event and one who didn't — the concordance index tells us how often the model correctly identifies which one was higher risk.

- **C-index = 0.50**: The model is no better than a coin flip
- **C-index = 0.65**: The model correctly ranks 65% of pairs (our minimum target)
- **C-index = 0.75**: The model correctly ranks 75% of pairs (good)
- **C-index = 0.85+**: Excellent predictive discrimination
